      DWAC
   =20
 =20

In October 2021, Trump Media & Technology Group  announced that it would go=
 public by merging=C2=A0with Digital World Acquisition Corp., a special pur=
pose acquisition company. This was certainly the first=C2=A0I had ever hear=
d of Trump Media & Technology Group, and I am pretty sure I am not alone. I=
t seemed, at the time, pretty half-baked. There were some plans for launchi=
ng a social media site called Truth Social, but it did not exist yet. There=
 was an investor presentation, but it was not replete with financial or bus=
iness information: I  pointed out that=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthere is not a single =
dollar sign in the whole deck.=E2=80=9D
Digital World Acquisition Corp., meanwhile, was a SPAC that had gone public=
 only a few weeks earlier. It had raised $287.5 million from investors, at =
$10 per share, to hunt for a company to take public. =E2=80=9CWe intend to =
focus on middle market and emerging growth technology-focused companies in =
the Americas, in SaaS and Technology or Fintech and Financial Services,=E2=
=80=9D  it told prospective investors. And: =E2=80=9CWe have not selected a=
ny specific business combination target and we have not, nor has anyone on =
our behalf, initiated any substantive discussions, directly or indirectly, =
with any business combination target.=E2=80=9D
This was,  it soon became apparent, a lie. When DWAC filed to go public, it=
s sponsor was already in serious talks with Trump=E2=80=99s people to take =
TMTG public. DWAC was not really a blind pool of cash looking for companies=
 to take public; it was a vehicle specifically for taking TMTG public.=C2=
=A0
You are not supposed to lie in securities filings, so last week DWAC  agree=
d to pay $18 million to the US Securities and Exchange Commission, if the d=
eal ever closes:

The Securities and Exchange Commission [Thursday] announced=C2=A0settled fr=
aud charges against Digital World Acquisition Corporation (DWAC), a special=
 purpose acquisition company (SPAC), for making material misrepresentations=
 in forms filed with the SEC as part of DWAC=E2=80=99s initial public offer=
ing and proposed merger with Trump Media & Technology Group Corp. (TMTG). T=
he Commission finds that DWAC misled investors and the SEC by failing to di=
sclose that it had formulated a plan to acquire and was pursuing the acquis=
ition of TMTG prior to DWAC=E2=80=99s IPO.
The purpose of a SPAC is to identify and acquire an operating business. As =
such, steps taken by a SPAC in furtherance of a particular acquisition are =
important to investors. According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, DWAC filed an=
 amended Form S-1 in support of its IPO in early September 2021 that stated=
 that neither DWAC nor its officers and directors had had any discussions w=
ith any potential target companies prior to the IPO. But, as found in the S=
EC=E2=80=99s order, dating back to February 2021, an individual who would l=
ater become DWAC=E2=80=99s CEO and Board Chairman, and others involved with=
 DWAC, had extensive SPAC merger discussions with TMTG. The SEC=E2=80=99s o=
rder further finds that, while DWAC=E2=80=99s CEO and Chairman initially pu=
rsued these discussions with TMTG on behalf of another SPAC, he created a p=
lan in the spring and summer of 2021 to potentially use DWAC to pursue a me=
rger with TMTG and used this plan to solicit certain pre-IPO investors. =E2=
=80=A6
=E2=80=9CDWAC failed to disclose its discussions with TMTG and failed to di=
sclose a material conflict of interest of its CEO and Chairman,=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0said Gurbir S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforce=
ment. =E2=80=9CIn the context of a SPAC =E2=80=93 a =E2=80=98blank-check=E2=
=80=99 entity without business operations =E2=80=93 these disclosure failur=
es are particularly problematic because investors focus on factors such as =
the SPAC=E2=80=99s management team and potential merger targets when making=
 financial decisions.=E2=80=9D

When we have   discussed this situation   previously, I have pointed out th=
at investors in DWAC were not really=C2=A0harmed=C2=A0by its lies.
  [3]
=C2=A0They bought DWAC stock at $10 in its public offering, thinking it was=
 a SPAC like any other, one that might or might not find an attractive deal=
. And then it quickly found the Trump deal and the stock shot up: The stock=
 closed at $9.96 the day before the Trump deal was announced, and $94.20 tw=
o days later.=C2=A0If you bought DWAC stock for $10 in its initial public o=
ffering, you were=C2=A0deceived=C2=A0about its plans, but in a=C2=A0nice=C2=
=A0way. You paid less for DWAC stock than it was worth. That=E2=80=99s good=
!
On the other hand =E2=80=A6=C2=A0why would DWAC do that? Why lie about its =
plans, in order to trick people into=C2=A0underpaying=C2=A0for the stock? I=
 don=E2=80=99t know, but let me suggest three possibilities.
One is just, like, sloppiness and incompetence? The standard form of SPAC p=
rospectus says =E2=80=9Cwe have not had any substantive conversations with =
any target,=E2=80=9D so they just copied and pasted that even though it was=
n=E2=80=99t true. Can=E2=80=99t really rule that out.
Another=C2=A0is insider trading. You=C2=A0are an executive at DWAC, you wan=
t DWAC to=C2=A0sell stock to raise money, and you want it to be too cheap s=
o that you can=C2=A0buy=C2=A0it cheaply, in the market, just before you ann=
ounce the deal, and then you=C2=A0make money when you announce the deal and=
 the stock pops. You want to trick people into thinking the stock is worth =
less than it is, so you can make informed trades on the other side.
This explanation doesn=E2=80=99t make very much sense,
  [4]
 and I mention it only because it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0appears to be true? We   t=
alked last month about a different  SEC enforcement action (and a related f=
ederal criminal prosecution), this one against a DWAC board member and his =
buddies, accusing them of insider trading by buying DWAC stock and warrants=
 on the open market before the Trump deal was announced. So, sure, I guess.
But I think the real reason is that DWAC probably couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0hav=
e done this deal without lying. It=E2=80=99s not just that DWAC lied in its=
 prospectus by saying it hadn=E2=80=99t had discussions with TMTG when it h=
ad. If it had told the truth =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it had said =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=
=80=99re a SPAC that=E2=80=99s raising money to take Trump Media & Technolo=
gy Group public=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0it wouldn=E2=80=99t have been allow=
ed to do its offering in the first place. A SPAC is supposed to be a blank-=
check company=C2=A0without=C2=A0any particular private company to take publ=
ic. If you are raising money to take one particular company public, that=E2=
=80=99s not a SPAC. That=E2=80=99s just a regular initial public offering. =
You don=E2=80=99t just file for a blank check; you file for an initial publ=
ic offering, with all of the regular disclosure about the company=E2=80=99s=
 business and finances.
Could TMTG have done a regular initial public offering in October 2021? No?=
 The investor presentation had no dollar signs. DWAC and TMTG eventually  f=
iled a prospectus describing=C2=A0TMTG=E2=80=99s business, but it took them=
 until May 2022. I=C2=A0  made fun of the prospectus=C2=A0at the time, beca=
use it was still not all that businesslike, and the stock is down about 60%=
 since that filing. And the SEC has been holding up the deal ever since =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0in part, clearly, because of the misstatements in DWAC=E2=80=99=
s original prospectus, but I suspect also a little bit because they have th=
eir doubts about the business disclosure. If TMTG had just filed for an ini=
tial public offering, I bet the SEC would have had lots of questions.
But meanwhile =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look, I do not use Truth Social, but I gather =
that it exists, at least in some=C2=A0minimal sense of the word. The fact t=
hat TMTG was announced to the world along with a $287.5=C2=A0million fundra=
ising, a public listing, and a stock price that shot up 840% in two days wa=
s=C2=A0useful=C2=A0to TMTG. It attracted attention, and employees, and user=
s, and hangers-on, and, not least, another   billion dollars of committed p=
rivate-investment-in-public equity (PIPE)=C2=A0financing (if the merger eve=
r closes) from, uh, institutional-ish investors. By launching as a vague id=
ea, rather than a fully formed company, TMTG was able to get enough attenti=
on and money and stock-market action to perhaps become a real company.
Also, to be clear, this SEC settlement is very=C2=A0good=C2=A0news for DWAC=
 and TMTG. Any resolution is good news; what was bad, for DWAC, was the lim=
bo that it was in with the SEC. The SEC has now signed off, at least in con=
cept, on the idea that DWAC=C2=A0can=C2=A0file some amended disclosure, get=
 a shareholder vote, and close its merger. When it does, TMTG gets DWAC=E2=
=80=99s $287.5 million, plus probably the $1 billion of PIPE money, plus a =
public stock-market listing and the ability to raise more money. The stock =
has drifted down since the glory days, but it closed at $20.08 on Friday, a=
fter the SEC settlement was announced, up 50% from the day before. There=E2=
=80=99s still some investor excitement here.
When this SPAC deal was first announced, back in October 2021,   I wrote th=
at =E2=80=9Cit does feel a little bit like all of recent financial history =
has been leading up to this moment.=E2=80=9D For instance, =E2=80=9Cmeme st=
ocks have prepared everyone for the notion that the value of a stock is bas=
ed on the fervor of its community of online fans, not its projected cash fl=
ows.=E2=80=9D TMTG is the purest form of meme stock: It launched as a meme =
stock before it was actually a company, and used its meme-stock status to s=
ort of, maybe, bootstrap its way into being a company.

