      X
   =20
 =20

Last year, when Elon Musk was toying with the idea of buying Twitter Inc. =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0asking to be on the board, quitting the board in a huff, say=
ing he would buy the company, saying he wouldn=E2=80=99t buy it, etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0he mused that, instead of buying Twitter, he could just start a=
 competing social media platform.
  [5]
 On the one hand, that seems kind of hard: Social networks are=C2=A0network=
=C2=A0businesses, and Twitter=E2=80=99s large=C2=A0user base and well-known=
 brand gave it a big head start over a hypothetical new Musk platform. On t=
he other hand, it=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0that=C2=A0hard: Twitter is a website, =
not a space rocket company; the basic mechanics of displaying a social feed=
 are reasonably well understood and easy to copy; Twitter=E2=80=99s users a=
re perpetually dissatisfied; Musk is a very famous person with a lot of fan=
s and followers. Could he hire a dozen engineers, spin up a Twitter clone, =
get a few million people to use it, and see if it developed into a real bus=
iness? Sure,=C2=A0maybe. Donald Trump did, sort of.
In the event, Musk spent $44 billion to actually acquire Twitter. Then he f=
ired most of the employees,=C2=A0drove away its celebrity users and is now =
  changing its name and logo:

Elon Musk has changed Twitter=E2=80=99s logo, replacing its signature blue =
bird with a stylized X as part of the billionaire=E2=80=99s vision of trans=
forming the 17-year-old service into an everything app. =E2=80=A6
While crowdsourcing the logo, Musk changed his profile information to read =
=E2=80=9CX.com,=E2=80=9D a web address that now redirects to corresponding =
user pages on twitter.com. The move is part of a broader overhaul that will=
 see all familiar =E2=80=9CTwitter=E2=80=9D and bird branding stripped away=
, he said. =E2=80=A6
The abrupt change comes as Twitter faces a steep decline in advertising dol=
lars and a new rival in Meta Platforms Inc.=E2=80=99s Threads, a service th=
at racked up 100 million users within five days of launching this month. Th=
e debut of Threads was greeted with derision by Musk, who=E2=80=99s accused=
 it of being a copycat service due to its similarities to Twitter.

I don=E2=80=99t know! I=E2=80=99ll kind of believe the everything app when =
I see it; certainly so far Musk has done a lot to make Twitter less useful =
but nothing, as far as I can see, to make it more useful. Adding payments t=
o Twitter=E2=80=99s messaging capability might be interesting in theory, bu=
t in real life=C2=A0Musk is  cutting back that messaging capability, so I d=
unno.=C2=A0
But if you traveled back in time two years and said =E2=80=9Ctwo years from=
 now, Twitter will no longer exist, and you will be able to choose between =
a Twitter-like service called =E2=80=98X=E2=80=99 run by Elon Musk and a Tw=
itter-like service called =E2=80=98Threads=E2=80=99 run by Facebook, which =
by the way will be  called Meta,=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99m not sure it=E2=80=99s=
 obvious=C2=A0that X is the winner there?
  [6]
=C2=A0Facebook/Meta/Mark Zuckerberg have a lot of experience running popula=
r social media platforms, and they employ a lot of people who have built so=
cial media platforms (some of them hired from Twitter!), while Musk mostly =
has experience tweeting (now called x=E2=80=99ing???)=C2=A0and employs stri=
kingly few people who have built social media platforms, because he fired=
=C2=A0most of them. There is a certain inertia that causes people to stay o=
n Twitter, but if you get rid of Twitter I=E2=80=99m not sure the inertia w=
ill fully carry over to X.
I guess my question is, what was he paying for?=C2=A0Musk didn=E2=80=99t wa=
nt Twitter for its employees (whom he fired) or its code (which he trashes =
regularly)=C2=A0or its brand=C2=A0(which he abandoned) or its most dedicate=
d=C2=A0users (whom he is working to drive away); he just wanted an entirely=
 different Twitter-like service. Surely he could have built that for less t=
han $44 billion? Mark Zuckerberg did!

